earch, the burgeoning of psychedelic art, drug-accompanied spiritual seeking, and a proliferation of drug subcultures. Elcock recounts stories of New Yorkers such as Holocaust survivor Nina Graboi and artist Isaac Abrams, whose lives were dramatically altered by their psychedelic experiences, while offering new insights into Timothy Leary’s role in turning on the city with psilocybin.Enlivened by personal stories and rooted in thoughtful analysis, Psychedelic New York is a multifaceted history of LSD and the urban psychedelic experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHallucinogenic drugszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aLSD (Drug)zNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aRecreational drug usezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aArt.  aBeat Generation.  aCounter-cultures.  aEast Village.  aGreenwich Village.  aIllegal.  aJazz.  aLight-shows.  aMedia.  aPsilocybin.  aPsychiatry.  aPsychoanalysis.  aSpirituality.  aSubcultures.  aTimothy Leary.  adrugs.  aperiod.  apostwar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228018032?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228018032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228018032/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles